To anyone who still supports her, question why you care more about a nostalgic attachment to a story about fictional magical wizard teens as opposed to real trans youth going through hell right now. And just stop. She's only relevant as a spokesperson for hate now. Nothing more.

You think women who are trans allies can't think or speak for themselves? Who on earth do you think you are? And why should anyone listen to you? Because you published a successful series decades ago and retroactively made one character in it gay when it was safe to do so?

If you cared about gay people and women at all,  and spefically gay women (you feel like you have some kind of ""authority"" to defend), you'd  take a look at our history and realise that we owe so much of our rights to trans people, that we share our histories with trans people.

As a gender non-conforming lesbian, #JKDoesntSpeakForMe . I have always found community and support alongside my trans siblings to define and embrace my own identity on my own terms. They fight for my rights and I  fight for theirs. Don't use me to justify your transphobia. Ever.

Anyway lemme clamber off my soapbox but also recommend your webtoon esp if it's under 1k subscribers and has awesome fantasy LGBTQI themes and I'll rec some stuff next update

Views are not everything but it's also kind of natural to want positive reinforcement and reach new readers. So platforms should actually maybe encourage and raise up the artists who post a page a week or 4 pages month.

Soooo idk. This is a long winded way of saying I appreciate my readers' patience even if the platform I am self publishing doesn't, I'm proud of the story I am telling and honestly it's probably time to also have a presence elsewhere and pursue the website idea
*per update not per page!

... hardly any attempt from webtoon canvas to promote my content and a huge drop in views. So idk really. It's the same everywhere I suppose and don't get me wrong, I deeply admire people who provide quantity, quality and regularity but I just can't hit all three currently.

In 2021 balancing work and other stuff with the comic naturally slowed the pace so instead of bursts of large content then hiatus I wanted to be more sustainable, maybe more so 10-12 panels per page. I'm a lot happier with that and pages are better quality. But...

But also quantity per update. In 2020 I was fully furloughed for 5 months and threw myself into increasingly large update we're talking 20 pages a WEEK. And sure the comic encountered success. But wow was that not sustainable at all! How did I do that?

Can't help but notice that in the first year of publishing GSoK on webtoon canvas my comic was promoted maybe 3-4 times despite the quality (obviously!) being subpar. I think in 2021 it was 1-2 times? Or once? Even though it's much better quality now. The difference? Regularity.

Not to wade into webcomics debate but the level quality doesn't feel like the issue (I think comics artists who are already aiming for print and artists improving a story as they go happily co-exist) but the frankly punishing expectations of weekly updates affecting visibility

Because we can talk about all of these things while also enacting Remembrance. It doesn't take away from the narrative - it expands it.

(And let's acknowledge that Toupie Lowther, as an upper-class white cis woman, benefited from a lot more privilege in her overall experience taking part in WWI, as harrowing as it was, and that fed into her later recognition).

Let's also talk about the fact that WWI propaganda propped up Joan of Arc as a figure to look up to for presumed male soldiers but were a bit more pragmatic when it came to celebrating women involved in conflict in their midst.

But let's also talk about the stories less told. Or the fact that nurses and ambulance drivers who were often women volunteers who wanted to *do* something if they couldn't fight were also literally on the frontlines, risking their lives.

The episode talks about many other things but what really struck me is that we always focus on the women "who fought" - like Marie Marvingt who dressed as a man on the frontlines but then also pioneered the air ambulance. Don't get me wrong - let's talk about her (because damn)

On this Armistice Day I'd like to invite you to find out more about Toupie Lowther, ambulance driver during WWI, but also a range of women in her position - women involved in WWI in a range of ways. https://t.co/VaT3b4cn40
